\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coordinate measuring machine
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the advent of computer-controlled machinery, engineers and machinists
 have been able to find very accurate measurements using a coordinate measuring
 machine, or CMM
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CMM"
description "Coordinate-measuring machine"

\end_inset

.
 Such machines bring a probe, usually a sphere of known size, in contact
 with the object being examined and register the machine's position when
 contact occurs.
 CMMs are often integrated into a computer-controlled milling machine in
 order to accurately measure the orientation of a part mounted within.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One disadvantage of the CMM is that it is time-consuming.
 The operator must preprogram the machine to measure specific data; for
 instance, the machine will have one mode for measuring width of a rectangular
 boss, another mode for measuring the diameter of a hole, and another mode
 for measuring the height of a feature.
 Even with such preprogramming, the machine may 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or make contact with the part being measured at a high speed.
 This usually breaks the probe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, CMMs generally may not be used for art digitization.
 Ancient sculptures and statues, often already very brittle or fragile,
 may flake when the probe is brought into contact.
 Plus, it would be prohibitively time-consuming to sample every point on
 the sculpture, since the probe must be brought into contact with every
 point it is to measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-contact measurements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advances in computer imaging techniques have made possible several measurement
 techniques that take advantage of optics and computer vision.
 Such techniques are much faster due to their ability to capture hundreds
 or even thousands of points at once in a single image.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Photo-based techniques
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach to recreating a 3D object in a computer model is to take photograph
s of the object, find correlations between them, and reconstruct the object
 based on these calculations.
 This approach, called photogrammetry, is highly useful in capturing environment
s in particular.
 A University of Washington doctoral thesis focused on pulling sets of images
 from Flickr, a popular photography site, to reconstruct famous locations
 throughout the world (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "Snavely"

\end_inset

).
 This work later formed the basis for Microsoft's PhotoSynth software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Photogrammetry is useful in that it can accept a wide range of input images.
 However, since it matches photos based on similar features, it is easy
 to induce error into a photo set.
 This error may be simply a slightly inaccurate measurement, or it may be
 a full, catastrophic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unwrapping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the object as described in the Snavely paper.
 Manual adjustment can alleviate the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unwrapping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem, but not the problem of inaccurate measurement.
 As such, this technique is useful for aesthetic reconstructions, but less
 than optimal for engineering applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Time-of-flight techniques
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another technique to measuring the shape of an object is an update to a
 relatively familiar technology: sonar
