\begin_layout Plain Layout
Radar is actually more similar to the time-of-flight technique, but its
 main application is in detecting the positions of aircraft, ignoring shape
 information.
 Sonar is used to capture the shape itself and is therefore a more suitable
 example.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Sonar works by sending a sound pulse through a medium, usually water, and
 recording the time of travel until the pulse returns.
 This data is used to recreate a shape, usually the shape of the bottom
 of a body of water.
\end_layout

